const A = [
{id:'modern-art-movements',title:'Key Modern Art Movements: Impressionism to Pop Art',cat:'arts',facts:[{stmt:'Impressionism (c.1865-1885), led by Monet, Renoir, and Degas, rejected academic painting conventions by emphasizing visible brushstrokes, ordinary subject matter, and the changing qualities of light captured en plein air.',src:'MoMA: Impressionism'},{stmt:'The Bauhaus school (1919-1933), founded by Walter Gropius in Weimar, Germany, unified fine arts, crafts, and industrial design under the principle that form follows function, profoundly influencing 20th-century architecture and design.',src:'Bauhaus-Archiv Berlin'},{stmt:'Pop Art emerged in the 1950s-60s as a reaction to Abstract Expressionism, with Andy Warhol and Roy Lichtenstein appropriating commercial imagery and mass media to blur the boundaries between high art and popular culture.',src:'Tate Modern: Pop Art'}],ps:[{title:'Art Since 1900: Modernism, Antimodernism, Postmodernism',type:'textbook',year:2016,inst:'Thames & Hudson',url:'https://thamesandhudson.com/art-since-1900-9780500239537'},{title:'Bauhaus: 1919-1933',type:'reference',year:2019,inst:'Museum of Modern Art',url:'https://www.moma.org/calendar/exhibitions/5127'}],gaps:['Contemporary post-internet art movements','Non-Western modern art traditions'],
body:`## TL;DR\nModern art movements from Impressionism to Pop Art transformed artistic expression from realistic representation to conceptual exploration.\n\n## Core Explanation\nImpressionism began with Monet, Renoir, and Degas painting outdoors to capture light. Cezanne bridged to Cubism (Picasso, Braque, 1907-1914). Surrealism (Dali, Magritte, 1920s) explored the unconscious. Bauhaus (1919-1933) unified art with industrial design. Abstract Expressionism (Pollock, Rothko, 1940s-50s) made the act of painting itself the subject.\n\n## Detailed Analysis\nPop Art (Warhol, Lichtenstein, 1960s) appropriated commercial imagery, marking the transition to postmodernism. Contemporary art exhibits pluralism: conceptual art, installation, performance, and digital art coexist without a dominant style.\n\n## Further Reading\n- MoMA Learning: Modern Art\n- The Art Story: Modern Art Movements Timeline\n- Tate: Art Terms`},

{id:'architecture-history',title:'History of Architecture: From Classical to Modern',cat:'arts',facts:[{stmt:'The three classical Greek architectural orders — Doric, Ionic, and Corinthian — established proportional systems that influenced Western architecture for over 2,500 years.',src:'Vitruvius: De Architectura'},{stmt:'The International Style, codified by Henry-Russell Hitchcock and Philip Johnson at the 1932 MoMA exhibition, defined modernist architecture through volume over mass, regularity over symmetry, and absence of applied ornament.',src:'MoMA International Style Exhibition'}],ps:[{title:'A Global History of Architecture, 3rd Edition',type:'textbook',year:2017,inst:'Wiley',url:'https://www.wiley.com/en-us/A+Global+History+of+Architecture%2C+3rd+Edition-p-9781118981337'},{title:'The International Style',type:'reference',year:1932,inst:'Museum of Modern Art',url:'https://www.moma.org/calendar/exhibitions/2044'}],gaps:['Vernacular architecture traditions','Sustainable/biophilic architecture movement'],
body:`## TL;DR\nArchitecture chronicles civilization evolution — from Greek temples to modern skyscrapers. Each era reflects its society values, materials, and engineering capabilities.\n\n## Core Explanation\nClassical tradition (Greek→Roman→Renaissance→Neoclassical) established proportion and order. Gothic architecture (12th-16th C) achieved unprecedented height through pointed arches and flying buttresses. Modernism (20th C) rejected ornament entirely — Le Corbusier's "machine for living" and Mies van der Rohe's "less is more."\n\n## Detailed Analysis\nPostmodernism (1970s-90s) reintroduced historical reference. Contemporary architecture navigates parametric design (Zaha Hadid), sustainable materials, and adaptive reuse. The Burj Khalifa (2010, 828m) demonstrates height limits remain unexplored.\n\n## Further Reading\n- ArchDaily: Architecture News\n- GreatBuildings.com: Architectural History\n- RIBA: Architecture Timeline`},

{id:'renaissance-art',title:'The Italian Renaissance: Art, Science, and Humanism',cat:'arts',facts:[{stmt:'The Italian Renaissance (c.1400-1600) began in Florence under Medici family patronage, funding artists including Botticelli, Michelangelo, and Leonardo da Vinci.',src:'Uffizi Gallery Archives'},{stmt:'Linear perspective, mathematically codified by Filippo Brunelleschi and formalized by Leon Battista Alberti in De Pictura (1435), enabled Renaissance artists to create convincing three-dimensional space on two-dimensional surfaces.',src:'National Gallery: Perspective'}],ps:[{title:'The Lives of the Artists',type:'literature',year:1550,inst:'Oxford University Press',url:'https://global.oup.com/academic/product/the-lives-of-the-artists-9780199537198'},{title:'Renaissance Art: A Very Short Introduction',type:'reference',year:2005,inst:'Oxford University Press',url:'https://global.oup.com/academic/product/renaissance-art-a-very-short-introduction-9780192803542'}],gaps:['Northern Renaissance comparison','Renaissance impact on scientific revolution'],
body:`## TL;DR\nThe Italian Renaissance was a comprehensive reorientation of European thought — valuing human capability, empirical observation, and classical learning.\n\n## Core Explanation\nThree innovations define Renaissance art: linear perspective (mathematical depth), chiaroscuro (light-shadow modeling), and sfumato (smoky transitions, Leonardo's signature). Oil paint enabled greater luminosity. Patrons — the Church and wealthy merchants — commissioned works celebrating religious devotion and secular power.\n\n## Detailed Analysis\nMichelangelo's Sistine Chapel ceiling (1508-1512) synthesizes classical form with Christian narrative across 300 figures. Raphael's School of Athens depicts ancient philosophers in perspectival architectural setting. Donatello's bronze David (c.1440) revived free-standing nude sculpture after a millennium.\n\n## Further Reading\n- Uffizi Gallery Digital Archives\n- Khan Academy: Renaissance Art\n- National Gallery London: Renaissance Collection`},

{id:'contemporary-art-trends',title:'Contemporary Art Trends and the Digital Turn',cat:'arts',facts:[{stmt:'NFT art market volume reached $24.9 billion in 2021, with Beeple\'s "Everydays" selling for $69.3 million at Christie\'s.',src:'Christie\'s Auction House'},{stmt:'The US Copyright Office ruled in 2023 that AI-generated images without sufficient human creative input cannot be copyrighted, reshaping debates on digital authorship.',src:'US Copyright Office Review Board'}],ps:[{title:'Art in the Age of Machine Learning',type:'textbook',year:2021,inst:'MIT Press',url:'https://mitpress.mit.edu/9780262046183/'},{title:'Christie\'s: Beeple Auction Record',type:'official_report',year:2021,inst:'Christie\'s',url:'https://www.christies.com/about-us/press-archive/details'}],gaps:['Virtual reality as artistic medium','Art market decentralization via blockchain'],
body:`## TL;DR\nContemporary art is defined by technological entanglement: NFTs transformed digital ownership, AI challenges human authorship, and social media reshapes curation.\n\n## Core Explanation\nPost-internet art emerged after 2008 (Hito Steyerl, Cory Arcangel). The NFT boom of 2021 demonstrated blockchain's capacity to create digital scarcity — and its volatility. AI art generators (2022+) reopened questions about creativity and authorship.\n\n## Detailed Analysis\nThe contemporary art market has decentralized geographically — major auctions now occur in Hong Kong, Dubai, and online alongside traditional New York/London centers. Social media has become a primary discovery channel, bypassing traditional gallery gatekeeping.\n\n## Further Reading\n- Art Basel: Market Reports\n- Rhizome: Net Art Anthology\n- Frieze: Contemporary Art Magazine`},

{id:'epidemiology-fundamentals',title:'Epidemiology: The Science of Public Health',cat:'health',facts:[{stmt:'John Snow\'s 1854 cholera investigation in London — mapping cases to the contaminated Broad Street pump — is considered the founding event of modern epidemiology.',src:'CDC Principles of Epidemiology'},{stmt:'The basic reproduction number (R0) represents average secondary infections from one case. COVID-19 ancestral strain had R0 2.5-3.0; measles has R0 12-18 — the most contagious known virus.',src:'WHO Epidemiology Handbook'}],ps:[{title:'Principles of Epidemiology in Public Health Practice, 3rd Ed',type:'textbook',year:2023,inst:'CDC',url:'https://www.cdc.gov/training-publichealth101/'},{title:'Basic Epidemiology, 2nd Edition',type:'textbook',year:2024,inst:'World Health Organization',url:'https://www.who.int/publications/i/item/9241547073'}],ss:[{title:'CDC Field Epidemiology Manual',type:'official_documentation',url:'https://www.cdc.gov/field-epi-manual/',inst:'CDC'}],gaps:['Molecular epidemiology advances','Digital surveillance ethics and privacy'],
body:`## TL;DR\nEpidemiology is the cornerstone of public health — the systematic study of disease distribution, determinants, and control in populations.\n\n## Core Explanation\nThe epidemiological triad (agent, host, environment) models disease causation. Study designs: descriptive (case reports, surveys), analytical (cohort, case-control), experimental (RCTs). Measures of association — relative risk, odds ratio — quantify exposure-outcome relationships.\n\n## Detailed Analysis\nKey metrics: incidence (new cases/period), prevalence (existing cases). Confounding, bias, and effect modification are primary validity threats. Bradford Hill\'s criteria (1965) provide a framework for assessing causation: temporality, dose-response, consistency, biological plausibility.\n\n## Further Reading\n- WHO Global Health Observatory\n- CDC Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report\n- The Lancet Infectious Diseases`},

{id:'sleep-science-and-circadian-rhythms',title:'Sleep Science and Circadian Rhythms',cat:'health',facts:[{stmt:'Sleep cycles alternate between NREM (stages N1-N3) and REM approximately every 90 minutes, with REM periods lengthening toward morning and deep slow-wave sleep dominating the first half of the night.',src:'NIH Sleep Research'},{stmt:'The suprachiasmatic nucleus (SCN) in the hypothalamus serves as the master circadian clock. Light exposure to intrinsically photosensitive retinal ganglion cells (ipRGCs) is the primary zeitgeber (time-giver).',src:'Journal of Biological Rhythms'}],ps:[{title:'Why We Sleep: Unlocking the Power of Sleep and Dreams',type:'textbook',year:2017,inst:'Scribner',url:'https://www.simonandschuster.com/books/Why-We-Sleep/Matthew-Walker/9781501144325'},{title:'Circadian Rhythms: A Very Short Introduction',type:'reference',year:2023,inst:'Oxford University Press',url:'https://global.oup.com/academic/product/circadian-rhythms-a-very-short-introduction-9780198787346'}],gaps:['Sleep role in glymphatic clearance','Individual chronotype genetics'],
body:`## TL;DR\nSleep is an active biological process essential for memory consolidation, metabolic regulation, and immune function. The circadian system orchestrates daily timing of sleep, hormone release, and gene expression.\n\n## Core Explanation\nTwo-process model: Process S (homeostatic sleep pressure) and Process C (circadian alerting signal). Adenosine accumulation drives Process S — caffeine blocks adenosine receptors. Melatonin from the pineal gland signals darkness, promoting sleep onset.\n\n## Detailed Analysis\nChronic sleep deprivation (<7 hours/night) associates with increased cardiovascular disease (45%), type 2 diabetes (30%), and all-cause mortality risk. REM sleep is critical for emotional memory processing; deep NREM consolidates declarative memories through hippocampal-neocortical dialogue.\n\n## Further Reading\n- NIH National Center for Sleep Disorders Research\n- Sleep Foundation: Science of Sleep\n- Nature Reviews Neuroscience: Sleep Special Collection`},

{id:'mental-health-fundamentals',title:'Mental Health: Disorders, Treatments, and Neurobiology',cat:'health',facts:[{stmt:'The WHO estimates 1 in 8 people globally (approximately 970 million) lived with a mental disorder in 2019, with anxiety disorders and depression being the most prevalent.',src:'WHO World Mental Health Report 2022'},{stmt:'SSRIs — including fluoxetine (Prozac), sertraline (Zoloft), and escitalopram (Lexapro) — are first-line treatments for depression, acting by blocking serotonin transporter (SERT) reuptake to increase synaptic serotonin availability.',src:'Nature Reviews Drug Discovery'}],ps:[{title:'DSM-5-TR',type:'standard',year:2022,inst:'American Psychiatric Association',url:'https://www.psychiatry.org/psychiatrists/practice/dsm'},{title:'World Mental Health Report 2022',type:'official_report',year:2022,inst:'WHO',url:'https://www.who.int/publications/i/item/9789240049338'}],gaps:['Microbiome-gut-brain axis in psychiatric disorders','Psychedelic-assisted psychotherapy evidence'],
body:`## TL;DR\nMental health encompasses emotional, psychological, and social well-being. The biopsychosocial model recognizes mental disorders arise from genetic vulnerability, neurobiological dysfunction, psychological factors, and social determinants.\n\n## Core Explanation\nMajor categories: mood disorders (depression, bipolar), anxiety disorders, psychotic disorders (schizophrenia), trauma-related disorders (PTSD), neurodevelopmental disorders (ADHD, autism). Evidence-based treatments combine pharmacotherapy with psychotherapy (CBT, DBT).\n\n## Detailed Analysis\nThe monoamine hypothesis guided antidepressant development for decades; newer research emphasizes neuroplasticity, inflammation, and HPA axis dysregulation. Ketamine\'s rapid antidepressant effects (within hours vs. weeks for SSRIs) demonstrated glutamatergic NMDA receptor modulation as a novel mechanism.\n\n## Further Reading\n- NIMH: Mental Health Information\n- The Lancet Psychiatry\n- APA: Practice Guidelines`},

{id:'plate-tectonics-theory',title:'Plate Tectonics: The Unifying Theory of Earth Sciences',cat:'geography',facts:[{stmt:'Earth\'s lithosphere is divided into approximately 15 major tectonic plates moving at 2-10 cm/year — about the speed fingernails grow. The theory was accepted in the 1960s after seafloor spreading evidence confirmed Wegener\'s continental drift hypothesis.',src:'USGS This Dynamic Earth'},{stmt:'Alfred Wegener proposed continental drift in 1912 based on matching coastlines, fossil distributions, and geological formations. His theory was rejected for 50 years until seafloor magnetic striping provided mechanism evidence.',src:'Britannica: Plate Tectonics'}],ps:[{title:'This Dynamic Earth: The Story of Plate Tectonics',type:'official_report',year:2023,inst:'USGS',url:'https://pubs.usgs.gov/gip/dynamic/dynamic.html'},{title:'Plate Tectonics: An Insider\'s History',type:'textbook',year:2018,inst:'Columbia University Press',url:'https://cup.columbia.edu/book/plate-tectonics/9780231111655'}],gaps:['Mantle convection drivers','Plate tectonics on other planets'],
body:`## TL;DR\nPlate tectonics is the unifying theory of geology, explaining earthquakes, volcanoes, mountain building, and fossil distribution. Earth is unique in the solar system in having active plate tectonics.\n\n## Core Explanation\nThree boundary types: divergent (plates move apart — Mid-Atlantic Ridge), convergent (plates collide — Himalayas, Andes), transform (plates slide past — San Andreas Fault). Seafloor spreading at mid-ocean ridges is balanced by subduction at trenches.\n\n## Detailed Analysis\nThe Wilson Cycle describes ocean basin lifecycle: rifting→spreading→subduction→collision (200-500 million years). Supercontinent cycle: Pangaea (335-175 Ma) preceded by Rodinia (1.3-0.75 Ga). Plate tectonics recycles crust and regulates climate over geological timescales.\n\n## Further Reading\n- USGS Earthquake Hazards Program\n- NOAA Ocean Explorer: Plate Tectonics\n- National Geographic: Plate Tectonics`},

{id:'climate-zones-and-biomes',title:'Global Climate Zones and Terrestrial Biomes',cat:'geography',facts:[{stmt:'The Koppen climate classification system categorizes world climates into five main groups: Tropical (A), Dry (B), Temperate (C), Continental (D), and Polar (E), based on temperature and precipitation patterns.',src:'NOAA Climate.gov'},{stmt:'Terrestrial biomes — tundra, taiga/boreal forest, temperate forest, grassland, desert, tropical rainforest — are defined by climate and characterized by distinct plant communities that determine the entire ecosystem structure.',src:'NASA Earth Observatory'}],ps:[{title:'Biogeography: Introduction to Space, Time, and Life',type:'textbook',year:2022,inst:'Wiley',url:'https://www.wiley.com/en-us/Biogeography-p-9781119464730'},{title:'Koppen Climate Classification',type:'reference',year:2024,inst:'NOAA',url:'https://www.climate.gov/koppen-climate-classification'}],gaps:['Climate change biome shift predictions','Microclimate classification refinement'],
body:`## TL;DR\nEarth\'s surface is divided into distinct climate zones and biomes with characteristic temperature, precipitation, and vegetation patterns. These zones are shifting poleward at unprecedented rates due to anthropogenic climate change.\n\n## Core Explanation\nThe Koppen system uses three-letter codes (e.g., Cfa = humid subtropical). The latitudinal climate gradient is modified by altitude (environmental lapse rate: ~6.5 C/km), ocean currents, and continentality.\n\n## Detailed Analysis\nClimate change shifts biome boundaries: boreal forests advance into tundra (Arctic greening), deserts expand into semi-arid zones, tropical species migrate upslope. The treeline advances uphill at ~5-10m/decade.\n\n## Further Reading\n- IPCC Sixth Assessment Report: Biomes\n- World Wildlife Fund: Terrestrial Ecoregions\n- Nature Climate Change`},

{id:'sports-exercise-physiology',title:'Exercise Physiology: How the Body Adapts to Training',cat:'sports',facts:[{stmt:'VO2max — maximum oxygen uptake during incremental exercise — is the gold standard measure of cardiorespiratory fitness. Elite endurance athletes reach 70-85 mL/kg/min vs. 35-45 for untrained individuals.',src:'American College of Sports Medicine'},{stmt:'Mitochondrial biogenesis is stimulated by endurance training through the PGC-1-alpha signaling pathway, increasing oxidative capacity by 50-100% within 8-12 weeks of consistent training.',src:'Journal of Applied Physiology'}],ps:[{title:'Exercise Physiology: Nutrition, Energy, and Human Performance, 9th Ed',type:'textbook',year:2022,inst:'Lippincott Williams & Wilkins',url:'https://www.lww.com/exercise-physiology-9781975217280'},{title:'ACSM Guidelines for Exercise Testing and Prescription, 11th Ed',type:'standard',year:2021,inst:'American College of Sports Medicine',url:'https://www.acsm.org/'}],gaps:['Molecular mechanisms of muscle hypertrophy','Sex differences in training response'],
body:`## TL;DR\nExercise physiology explains how cardiovascular, respiratory, muscular, and endocrine systems adapt to training stress. These adaptations are the biological basis for improved athletic performance and health.\n\n## Core Explanation\nThe FITT principle (Frequency, Intensity, Time, Type) guides training prescription. Overload triggers the General Adaptation Syndrome: alarm→resistance→exhaustion. Specificity means training adaptations match the demands imposed.\n\n## Detailed Analysis\nEnergy systems continuum: ATP-PCr (0-10s), glycolytic (10-120s), oxidative (>2min). Lactate is now understood as a valuable fuel source (lactate shuttle theory). Heart rate variability (HRV) monitoring guides training load management.\n\n## Further Reading\n- ACSM Position Stands\n- Journal of Strength and Conditioning Research\n- Sports Medicine (Springer)`},

{id:'sports-nutrition',title:'Sports Nutrition: Fueling Performance and Recovery',cat:'sports',facts:[{stmt:'Carbohydrate loading — consuming 8-12 g/kg body weight of carbs in the 24-48 hours before competition — can increase muscle glycogen stores by 50-100% and improve endurance performance by 2-4% in events lasting over 90 minutes.',src:'International Society of Sports Nutrition'},{stmt:'Protein timing around exercise (20-40g within 2 hours post-exercise) maximizes muscle protein synthesis. Leucine, at a threshold of ~2-3g per meal, is the key amino acid triggering the mTOR signaling pathway.',src:'JISSN'}],ps:[{title:'Advanced Sports Nutrition, 3rd Edition',type:'textbook',year:2020,inst:'Human Kinetics',url:'https://www.humankinetics.com/advanced-sports-nutrition/'},{title:'ISSN Position Stand: Nutrient Timing',type:'standard',year:2023,inst:'ISSN',url:'https://jissn.biomedcentral.com/'}],gaps:['Personalized nutrition based on genetic profiles','Microbiome manipulation for performance'],
body:`## TL;DR\nSports nutrition optimizes timing, quantity, and composition of nutrient intake to maximize training adaptations, competition performance, and recovery.\n\n## Core Explanation\nMacronutrient targets vary by sport: endurance athletes need 8-12 g/kg/day carbs; strength athletes need 1.6-2.2 g/kg/day protein. Fat provides essential fatty acids. Glycogen is the limiting fuel for high-intensity exercise — depletion (hitting the wall) occurs at ~2,000 kcal stored glycogen.\n\n## Detailed Analysis\nHydration: as little as 2% body mass loss impairs cognitive and physical performance. Electrolyte replacement (sodium 500-700 mg/L) needed for exercise >2 hours. Caffeine (3-6 mg/kg) is the most researched legal ergogenic aid, improving endurance by 3-5%.\n\n## Further Reading\n- IOC Consensus Statement: Sports Nutrition\n- Gatorade Sports Science Institute\n- ISSN Conferences and Position Papers`},

{id:'olympic-games-history',title:'History of the Modern Olympic Games',cat:'sports',facts:[{stmt:'The modern Olympic Games were revived by Pierre de Coubertin in 1896 in Athens with 241 athletes from 14 nations. The 2024 Paris Olympics featured 10,500 athletes from 206 nations in 329 events across 32 sports.',src:'International Olympic Committee'},{stmt:'The Olympic motto was updated in 2021 to "Citius, Altius, Fortius — Communiter" (Faster, Higher, Stronger — Together), adding "Communiter" to emphasize solidarity following the COVID-19 pandemic.',src:'IOC Olympic Charter 2024'}],ps:[{title:'The Olympic Games: A Social Science Perspective',type:'textbook',year:2023,inst:'Routledge',url:'https://www.routledge.com/'},{title:'Olympic Charter 2024',type:'official_documentation',year:2024,inst:'IOC',url:'https://olympics.com/ioc/olympic-charter'}],gaps:['Political boycotts and their impact on Olympic movement','Environmental sustainability of mega-sporting events'],
body:`## TL;DR\nThe modern Olympic Games, revived in 1896, represent humanity\'s oldest continuous international sporting event, growing from 241 to 10,500 athletes over 128 years.\n\n## Core Explanation\nThe Olympic Movement operates through three pillars: IOC, International Sports Federations (IFs), and National Olympic Committees (NOCs). The Paralympic Games, held alongside since 1960, embody similar ideals for athletes with disabilities.\n\n## Detailed Analysis\nKey moments: Jesse Owens\' four gold medals at Berlin 1936 challenging Nazi ideology; the Black Power salute at Mexico City 1968; the Miracle on Ice (1980); Barcelona 1992 — first Games without boycotts since 1972. Gender equality reached parity at Tokyo 2020.\n\n## Further Reading\n- IOC Official Website\n- Olympic Studies Centre\n- Journal of Olympic History`},

{id:'decision-making-psychology',title:'The Psychology of Decision Making',cat:'self-improvement',facts:[{stmt:'Daniel Kahneman and Amos Tversky\'s prospect theory (1979) demonstrated loss aversion — losses feel ~2x more painful than equivalent gains feel pleasurable — one of the most replicated findings in behavioral economics.',src:'Science (1979)'},{stmt:'The dual-process theory distinguishes System 1 (fast, automatic, intuitive) from System 2 (slow, deliberate, analytical). System 1 makes ~95% of daily decisions, using efficient but systematically biased heuristics.',src:'Thinking, Fast and Slow (Kahneman, 2011)'}],ps:[{title:'Thinking, Fast and Slow',type:'textbook',year:2011,inst:'Farrar, Straus and Giroux',url:'https://us.macmillan.com/books/9780374533557/thinkingfastandslow'},{title:'Prospect Theory: An Analysis of Decision under Risk',type:'academic_paper',year:1979,inst:'Econometrica',url:'https://www.jstor.org/stable/1914185'}],gaps:['Neuroscience of decision making','Group decision-making dynamics'],
body:`## TL;DR\nHuman decision making is shaped by cognitive biases — systematic deviations from rationality affecting everything from financial choices to medical diagnoses.\n\n## Core Explanation\nKey biases: anchoring (over-relying on first information), confirmation bias (seeking confirming evidence), availability heuristic (overestimating memorable events), framing effects, sunk cost fallacy.\n\n## Detailed Analysis\nDebiasing strategies: considering the opposite, premortem analysis, decision matrices, structured analytic techniques. The WRAP framework (Widen options, Reality-test assumptions, Attain distance, Prepare to be wrong) provides practical decision-making process.\n\n## Further Reading\n- Kahneman, Lovallo, Sibony: Before You Make That Big Decision (HBR)\n- Decision Science News\n- Center for Decision Research (Chicago Booth)`},

{id:'emotional-intelligence',title:'Emotional Intelligence: Theory and Applications',cat:'self-improvement',facts:[{stmt:'Daniel Goleman\'s emotional intelligence model identifies five components: self-awareness, self-regulation, motivation, empathy, and social skills. Meta-analyses find EQ predicts job performance in interpersonal roles approximately 2x better than IQ.',src:'Harvard Business Review (Goleman, 1998)'},{stmt:'The Mayer-Salovey-Caruso ability-based model defines EQ as four abilities: perceiving emotions, using emotions to facilitate thought, understanding emotions, and managing emotions — measured through performance tests rather than self-report.',src:'MSCEIT Technical Manual'}],ps:[{title:'Emotional Intelligence: Why It Can Matter More Than IQ',type:'textbook',year:1995,inst:'Bantam Books',url:'https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/557457/emotional-intelligence-by-daniel-goleman/'},{title:'What Makes a Leader? (HBR Classic)',type:'academic_paper',year:1998,inst:'Harvard Business Review',url:'https://hbr.org/2004/01/what-makes-a-leader'}],gaps:['Cultural variations in emotional expression norms','AI-based EQ training tools efficacy'],
body:`## TL;DR\nEmotional intelligence (EQ) — the capacity to recognize, understand, and manage emotions — is a stronger predictor of leadership effectiveness and relationship satisfaction than cognitive intelligence alone.\n\n## Core Explanation\nSelf-awareness begins with recognizing emotional triggers. Self-regulation involves cognitive reappraisal and response modulation. Empathy — both cognitive and emotional — underpins social effectiveness.\n\n## Detailed Analysis\nEQ development: mindfulness meditation (increases interoceptive awareness), journaling, active listening (improves empathy), feedback-seeking. Google\'s Project Oxygen found technical expertise ranked LAST among eight key management behaviors.\n\n## Further Reading\n- Consortium for Research on Emotional Intelligence\n- Yale Center for Emotional Intelligence\n- Journal of Organizational Behavior`},

{id:'cognitive-biases-handbook',title:'Cognitive Biases: A Practical Guide to Clearer Thinking',cat:'self-improvement',facts:[{stmt:'The Dunning-Kruger effect (1999) demonstrates that individuals with low competence in a domain overestimate their ability while experts underestimate theirs. Students in the 12th percentile estimated their performance at the 62nd percentile.',src:'Journal of Personality and Social Psychology (1999)'},{stmt:'The mere exposure effect — repeated unreinforced exposure increases positive affect — underlies advertising effectiveness, musical taste formation, and interpersonal attraction.',src:'Zajonc, JPSP (1968)'}],ps:[{title:'The Art of Thinking Clearly',type:'textbook',year:2013,inst:'Harper',url:'https://www.harpercollins.com/products/the-art-of-thinking-clearly-rolf-dobelli'},{title:'Nudge: Improving Decisions About Health, Wealth, and Happiness',type:'textbook',year:2009,inst:'Yale University Press',url:'https://yalebooks.yale.edu/book/9780300122237/nudge/'}],gaps:['Cultural variation in bias expression','AI-assisted debiasing tools'],
body:`## TL;DR\nCognitive biases are systematic errors in thinking affecting judgment and decision making. Over 180 documented biases influence everything from medical diagnoses to investment choices.\n\n## Core Explanation\nBias categories: information processing (anchoring, availability), belief formation (confirmation bias), social influence (bandwagon effect, groupthink), self-evaluation (overconfidence, self-serving bias).\n\n## Detailed Analysis\nDebiasing: premortem (imagine future failure), red teaming (designated challenger role), blind analysis, reference class forecasting (use base rates from similar past cases).\n\n## Further Reading\n- ClearerThinking.org (Spencer Greenberg)\n- Center for Applied Rationality\n- LessWrong Community Sequences`},

{id:'ancient-mesopotamia',title:'Ancient Mesopotamia: Cradle of Civilization',cat:'history',facts:[{stmt:'Mesopotamia — the land between the Tigris and Euphrates in modern Iraq — saw the world\'s first cities (Uruk, ~4000 BCE), first writing system (cuneiform, ~3200 BCE), and first legal codes.',src:'British Museum: Mesopotamia'},{stmt:'The Code of Hammurabi (~1754 BCE), inscribed on a 2.25m basalt stele, contains 282 laws following the principle of lex talionis and provides the most complete surviving legal code from the ancient Near East.',src:'Louvre Museum: Code of Hammurabi'}],ps:[{title:'Ancient Mesopotamia: Portrait of a Dead Civilization',type:'textbook',year:2018,inst:'University of Chicago Press',url:'https://press.uchicago.edu/ucp/books/book/chicago/A/bo3633333.html'},{title:'The Babylonian World',type:'reference',year:2022,inst:'Routledge',url:'https://www.routledge.com/The-Babylonian-World/Leick/p/book/9780415497903'}],gaps:['Environmental collapse theories of Mesopotamian decline','Women\'s roles in Mesopotamian society'],
body:`## TL;DR\nMesopotamia gave humanity its first cities, writing, legal codes, and mathematical systems. Sumerians, Akkadians, Babylonians, and Assyrians each built upon earlier innovations.\n\n## Core Explanation\nThe Sumerians developed the city-state model — Ur, Uruk, Lagash — each with patron deity and ziggurat. Cuneiform evolved from pictographs to abstract signs. The Epic of Gilgamesh (~2100 BCE) is literature\'s oldest surviving masterpiece.\n\n## Detailed Analysis\nInnovations: the wheel, plow agriculture, irrigation canal networks, standardized weights and measures, astronomical observation (60-minute hour, 360-degree circle). The Assyrian Empire created the first professional standing army with iron weapons.\n\n## Further Reading\n- British Museum: Mesopotamia Collection\n- Metropolitan Museum: Ancient Near Eastern Art\n- Cambridge Ancient History Series`},

{id:'ancient-egyptian-civilization',title:'Ancient Egyptian Civilization: Pharaohs, Pyramids, and Afterlife',cat:'history',facts:[{stmt:'Ancient Egyptian civilization spanned over 3,000 years (c.3100-30 BCE) across 31 dynasties. The Great Pyramid of Giza (c.2560 BCE) remained the tallest human-made structure for over 3,800 years at 146.6 meters.',src:'British Museum: Ancient Egypt'},{stmt:'The Rosetta Stone (196 BCE), deciphered by Jean-Francois Champollion in 1822, contained the same decree in three scripts — unlocking the ability to read Egyptian hieroglyphs after 1,500 years of obscurity.',src:'British Museum: Rosetta Stone'}],ps:[{title:'The Oxford History of Ancient Egypt',type:'textbook',year:2020,inst:'Oxford University Press',url:'https://global.oup.com/academic/product/the-oxford-history-of-ancient-egypt-9780192804587'},{title:'The Complete Gods and Goddesses of Ancient Egypt',type:'reference',year:2017,inst:'Thames & Hudson',url:'https://thamesandhudson.com/the-complete-gods-and-goddesses-of-ancient-egypt-9780500284247'}],gaps:['Pyramid construction engineering methods debate','Daily life of non-elite Egyptians'],
body:`## TL;DR\nAncient Egypt\'s 3,000-year civilization produced monumental architecture, sophisticated medicine, advanced mathematics, and a complex religious system centered on the afterlife.\n\n## Core Explanation\nEgyptian society was a theocratic monarchy. The concept of ma\'at (cosmic order, truth, justice) governed ethics and law. Hieroglyphic writing combined logographic and phonetic elements for monumental and religious inscriptions.\n\n## Detailed Analysis\nMummification reflected afterlife beliefs. The Book of the Dead provided spells for navigating the afterlife. Egyptian medicine was remarkably advanced: the Edwin Smith Papyrus (c.1600 BCE) describes 48 surgical cases with rational, observation-based treatments.\n\n## Further Reading\n- British Museum: Egyptian Collection\n- Theban Mapping Project\n- UCLA Encyclopedia of Egyptology`},

{id:'world-war-ii-overview',title:'World War II: Global Conflict and Its Aftermath',cat:'history',facts:[{stmt:'World War II (1939-1945) was the deadliest conflict in human history with an estimated 70-85 million fatalities. The Holocaust alone resulted in the systematic murder of 6 million Jews by Nazi Germany.',src:'United States Holocaust Memorial Museum'},{stmt:'The D-Day invasion (June 6, 1944) was the largest amphibious military operation in history: 156,000 Allied troops crossed the English Channel, supported by 11,590 aircraft and 6,939 naval vessels.',src:'Imperial War Museum: D-Day'}],ps:[{title:'The Second World War',type:'textbook',year:2012,inst:'Little, Brown',url:'https://www.littlebrown.com/titles/antony-beevor/the-second-world-war/9780316023740/'},{title:'The Rise and Fall of the Third Reich',type:'textbook',year:1960,inst:'Simon & Schuster',url:'https://www.simonandschuster.com/books/The-Rise-and-Fall-of-the-Third-Reich/William-L-Shirer/9781451651683'}],gaps:['Comfort women and Asian theater atrocities acknowledgment','Postwar reconstruction comparative analysis'],
body:`## TL;DR\nWorld War II reshaped the global order — ending European colonial empires, establishing US-Soviet superpowers, creating the United Nations, and setting the stage for the Cold War.\n\n## Core Explanation\nCauses: punitive Treaty of Versailles, Great Depression radicalization, fascist expansionism, appeasement failure. The war began with Germany\'s invasion of Poland (September 1, 1939).\n\n## Detailed Analysis\nThe Pacific War (1941-1945) was defined by naval aviation and island-hopping. The Manhattan Project developed atomic weapons — Hiroshima and Nagasaki forced Japan\'s surrender. Yalta and Potsdam divided Europe into Western and Soviet spheres.\n\n## Further Reading\n- Imperial War Museum WWII Collections\n- US Holocaust Memorial Museum\n- National WWII Museum (New Orleans)`},

{id:'data-science-fundamentals',title:'Data Science: Methods, Tools, and Best Practices',cat:'science',facts:[{stmt:'The CRISP-DM methodology (1996) defines six phases: business understanding, data understanding, data preparation, modeling, evaluation, and deployment — and remains the most widely used data science workflow framework.',src:'KDnuggets Industry Survey 2023'},{stmt:'The "curse of dimensionality" — as features increase, data becomes exponentially sparse. Dimensionality reduction techniques (PCA, t-SNE, UMAP) are essential countermeasures.',src:'Elements of Statistical Learning'}],ps:[{title:'Python for Data Analysis, 3rd Edition',type:'textbook',year:2022,inst:'O\'Reilly Media',url:'https://www.oreilly.com/library/view/python-for-data/9781098104023/'},{title:'The Elements of Statistical Learning, 2nd Edition',type:'textbook',year:2009,inst:'Springer',url:'https://link.springer.com/book/10.1007/978-0-387-84858-7'}],gaps:['Responsible AI and fairness in data science','Real-time data pipeline architectures'],
body:`## TL;DR\nData science combines statistics, computer science, and domain expertise to extract insights from data. The modern workflow — from data wrangling through machine learning to deployment — is supported by Python\'s ecosystem and cloud infrastructure.\n\n## Core Explanation\nThe data science lifecycle: problem formulation→data acquisition→cleaning→EDA→feature engineering→modeling→evaluation→deployment→monitoring. Data quality is the dominant determinant of project success — "garbage in, garbage out."\n\n## Detailed Analysis\nStatistical foundations: probability distributions, hypothesis testing, confidence intervals. ML paradigms: supervised (classification, regression), unsupervised (clustering, dimensionality reduction), reinforcement learning. Model evaluation must match business objectives.\n\n## Further Reading\n- Kaggle: Data Science Competitions\n- Towards Data Science\n- Journal of Data Science`},

{id:'scientific-method',title:'The Scientific Method: From Hypothesis to Theory',cat:'science',facts:[{stmt:'Karl Popper\'s falsification criterion (1934) states that scientific theories cannot be proven true, only falsified — a hypothesis is scientific only if it makes predictions that could potentially be shown false.',src:'The Logic of Scientific Discovery (Popper, 1934)'},{stmt:'The replication crisis in psychology and biomedical sciences — with landmark replication attempts finding only 36-62% of findings reproducible — has catalyzed reforms including preregistration and data sharing mandates.',src:'Open Science Collaboration, Science (2015)'}],ps:[{title:'The Logic of Scientific Discovery',type:'textbook',year:1934,inst:'Routledge',url:'https://www.routledge.com/The-Logic-of-Scientific-Discovery/Popper/p/book/9780415278447'},{title:'The Structure of Scientific Revolutions',type:'textbook',year:1962,inst:'University of Chicago Press',url:'https://press.uchicago.edu/ucp/books/book/chicago/S/bo13179781.html'}],gaps:['Bayesian vs frequentist philosophy of science','Citizen science methodology validation'],
body:`## TL;DR\nThe scientific method — observation→question→hypothesis→experiment→analysis→conclusion — is humanity\'s most reliable path to knowledge. Its power lies not in proving theories true, but in systematically eliminating false ones.\n\n## Core Explanation\nThomas Kuhn\'s paradigm shift model (1962) describes scientific progress as revolutionary transitions: normal science operates within paradigms until anomalies trigger crisis, resolved by adopting new paradigms.\n\n## Detailed Analysis\nModern reforms address weaknesses: p-hacking, publication bias, low statistical power. Open Science: preregistration, data/code sharing, preprint servers (arXiv, bioRxiv), Registered Reports (peer review before results known).\n\n## Further Reading\n- Center for Open Science\n- Nature: Methods & Protocols\n- Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy: Scientific Method`},

{id:'neuroscience-brain-plasticity',title:'Neuroscience: Neuroplasticity and Brain Function',cat:'science',facts:[{stmt:'Neuroplasticity — the brain\'s ability to reorganize synaptic connections — persists throughout life. London taxi drivers showed enlarged posterior hippocampi proportional to years of navigation experience (Maguire et al., PNAS, 2000).',src:'Maguire et al., PNAS (2000)'},{stmt:'Long-term potentiation (LTP), discovered by Bliss and Lomo in 1973, is the persistent strengthening of synapses — widely considered the primary cellular mechanism underlying learning and memory.',src:'Bliss & Lomo, Journal of Physiology (1973)'}],ps:[{title:'Principles of Neural Science, 6th Edition',type:'textbook',year:2021,inst:'McGraw-Hill',url:'https://www.mheducation.com/highered/product/principles-neural-science-kandel-koester/M9781259642234.html'},{title:'The Brain That Changes Itself',type:'textbook',year:2007,inst:'Penguin',url:'https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/27972/the-brain-that-changes-itself-by-norman-doidge/'}],gaps:['Neuroplasticity limits and critical period mechanisms','Neurogenesis in adult humans debate'],
body:`## TL;DR\nNeuroplasticity — the brain\'s lifelong capacity to reorganize structure and function — is the biological basis of learning, memory, and recovery from injury.\n\n## Core Explanation\nPlasticity operates at synaptic, cellular, and systems levels. Hebb\'s rule — "neurons that fire together, wire together" — captures the associative principle underlying LTP. The adult brain generates ~700 new neurons daily in the hippocampus.\n\n## Detailed Analysis\nEnvironmental enrichment — exercise, cognitive stimulation, social interaction — upregulates BDNF, promoting plasticity. Constraint-induced movement therapy exploits plasticity to rehabilitate stroke patients by forcing use of the affected limb.\n\n## Further Reading\n- Society for Neuroscience: BrainFacts.org\n- Nature Neuroscience\n- Allen Institute for Brain Science`},

{id:'strategic-management-theory',title:'Strategic Management: Frameworks and Practice',cat:'business',facts:[{stmt:'Michael Porter\'s Five Forces framework (1979) analyzes industry competitiveness through: threat of new entrants, supplier power, buyer power, substitute threat, and competitive rivalry.',src:'Porter, Harvard Business Review (1979)'},{stmt:'Peter Drucker\'s Management by Objectives (MBO), introduced in The Practice of Management (1954), proposed employees perform better when participating in setting their own goals — a precursor to modern OKRs used by Google and Intel.',src:'Drucker, The Practice of Management (1954)'}],ps:[{title:'Competitive Strategy: Techniques for Analyzing Industries and Competitors',type:'textbook',year:1980,inst:'Free Press',url:'https://www.simonandschuster.com/books/Competitive-Strategy/Michael-E-Porter/9780684005278'},{title:'The Practice of Management',type:'textbook',year:1954,inst:'Harper & Row',url:'https://www.harpercollins.com/'}],gaps:['Agile strategy in fast-changing digital markets','Platform business model strategy'],
body:`## TL;DR\nStrategic management defines how organizations create and sustain competitive advantage through analytical frameworks and disciplined execution.\n\n## Core Explanation\nStrategy formulation: external analysis (PESTEL), internal analysis (VRIO: Valuable, Rare, Inimitable, Organizationally exploited resources), strategy selection (cost leadership, differentiation, focus). The resource-based view argues sustainable advantage derives from unique internal resources.\n\n## Detailed Analysis\nBlue Ocean Strategy advocates creating uncontested market space. McKinsey estimates 70% of strategic initiatives fail due to execution issues. OKRs (Objectives and Key Results) align organizational effort with measurable outcomes.\n\n## Further Reading\n- Harvard Business Review: Strategy Collection\n- McKinsey Quarterly\n- Strategic Management Journal`},

{id:'leadership-and-organizational-behavior',title:'Leadership Theory and Organizational Behavior',cat:'business',facts:[{stmt:'Transformational leadership, articulated by Burns (1978) and Bass (1985), engages followers through idealized influence, inspirational motivation, intellectual stimulation, and individualized consideration — the most effective style per meta-analysis of 626 studies.',src:'Bass & Riggio, Transformational Leadership (2006)'},{stmt:'Google\'s Project Oxygen found technical expertise ranked LAST among eight key management behaviors. Coaching, empowerment, and creating inclusive environments were top predictors of team effectiveness.',src:'Google re:Work (Garvin, 2013)'}],ps:[{title:'Transformational Leadership, 2nd Edition',type:'textbook',year:2006,inst:'Psychology Press',url:'https://www.routledge.com/Transformational-Leadership/Bass-Riggio/p/book/9780805847628'},{title:'Organizational Behavior, 18th Edition',type:'textbook',year:2018,inst:'Pearson',url:'https://www.pearson.com/en-us/subject-catalog/p/organizational-behavior/P200000005179'}],gaps:['Remote/hybrid leadership adaptation','Cross-cultural leadership effectiveness variations'],
body:`## TL;DR\nLeadership is not innate — it\'s a set of learnable behaviors. Modern leadership theory has shifted from trait-based models to behavioral, situational, and transformational approaches.\n\n## Core Explanation\nLeadership theory evolution: trait theories (1940s)→behavioral theories (1950s)→contingency theories (1960s-70s)→transformational leadership (1980s)→authentic/ethical/servant leadership (2000s).\n\n## Detailed Analysis\nPsychological safety was identified by Google\'s Project Aristotle as the #1 predictor of team performance. Intrinsic motivation (autonomy, mastery, purpose) outperforms extrinsic rewards for complex cognitive work.\n\n## Further Reading\n- Harvard Business Review: Leadership\n- Center for Creative Leadership\n- Academy of Management Journal`},

{id:'western-ethics-tradition',title:'Western Ethical Tradition: Aristotle, Kant, and Utilitarianism',cat:'arts',facts:[{stmt:'Aristotle\'s virtue ethics (Nicomachean Ethics, c.350 BCE) defines the good life (eudaimonia) as activity of the soul in accordance with virtue, achieved through the Doctrine of the Mean.',src:'Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy: Aristotle\'s Ethics'},{stmt:'Kant\'s categorical imperative (1785) provides a universal test: "Act only according to that maxim whereby you can at the same time will that it should become a universal law."',src:'Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy: Kant\'s Moral Philosophy'}],ps:[{title:'Nicomachean Ethics',type:'literature',year:-350,inst:'Oxford University Press',url:'https://global.oup.com/academic/product/nicomachean-ethics-9780199213610'},{title:'Groundwork of the Metaphysics of Morals',type:'literature',year:1785,inst:'Cambridge University Press',url:'https://www.cambridge.org/9781107008519'}],gaps:['Feminist ethics critique','Applied ethics in AI and technology'],
body:`## TL;DR\nThe Western ethical tradition is dominated by three approaches: virtue ethics (Aristotle — character), deontology (Kant — duty), and consequentialism/utilitarianism (Bentham/Mill — outcomes). Contemporary ethics integrates elements of all three.\n\n## Core Explanation\nAristotle: flourishing (eudaimonia) through cultivating virtues. Kant: moral worth from acting from duty, treating persons as ends. Utilitarianism: maximizing overall happiness.\n\n## Detailed Analysis\nThe trolley problem illustrates deontological vs. utilitarian reasoning. Bioethics — informed consent, patient autonomy, resource allocation — draws on all three traditions. Effective altruism represents a modern utilitarian movement.\n\n## Further Reading\n- Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy (free, peer-reviewed)\n- Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy\n- Justice (HarvardX — Michael Sandel)`},

{id:'political-philosophy',title:'Political Philosophy: Justice, Liberty, and the Social Contract',cat:'arts',facts:[{stmt:'John Rawls\' A Theory of Justice (1971) proposes the "original position" thought experiment — what principles would rational people choose behind a "veil of ignorance"? Result: the liberty principle and the difference principle.',src:'Rawls, A Theory of Justice (1971)'},{stmt:'Thomas Hobbes\' Leviathan (1651) introduced social contract theory: without government, life would be "solitary, poor, nasty, brutish, and short." Rational individuals consent to be governed for security.',src:'Hobbes, Leviathan (1651)'}],ps:[{title:'A Theory of Justice',type:'textbook',year:1971,inst:'Harvard University Press',url:'https://www.hup.harvard.edu/catalog.php?isbn=9780674000780'},{title:'Leviathan',type:'literature',year:1651,inst:'Cambridge University Press',url:'https://www.cambridge.org/9780521567978'}],gaps:['Non-Western political philosophy traditions','Digital governance and platform democracy'],
body:`## TL;DR\nPolitical philosophy addresses fundamental questions of governance: What is justice? What justifies state authority? The social contract tradition — Hobbes through Locke and Rousseau to Rawls — provides the dominant Western framework.\n\n## Core Explanation\nHobbes argued for absolute sovereignty. Locke countered with natural rights justifying revolution. Rousseau emphasized the general will. Rawls synthesized social contract theory with distributive justice.\n\n## Detailed Analysis\nNozick\'s libertarian critique argues only a minimal state is justified. Communitarianism (Sandel, MacIntyre) critiques liberalism\'s abstract individualism.\n\n## Further Reading\n- Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy: Political Philosophy\n- The Harvard Justice Course (Michael Sandel, free online)\n- Philosophy Bites Podcast`},
];

let n = 0, sk = 0;
